  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations - A set of global standards for preventing money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC) - Provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime.\n\n3. United Nations Convention Against Corruption (UNCAC) - Includes provisions to prevent and criminalize money laundering.\n\n4. Basel Committee's Core Principles - Provides guidelines for banking supervision and anti-money laundering practices.\n\n5. The Wolfsberg Principles - A set of guidelines for preventing money laundering in banking.\n\nMany countries have also implemented their own national laws based on these international standards, such as:\n\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- The Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) in the United Kingdom\n- Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations in the European Union\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs",
